Europe needs a fresh wave of immigration.
More than 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year, starting from Brussels.
More than 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year, starting from Brussels.
Greek Lesbos Island's refugee and migrant camps are overcrowded, and the conditions at other Libyan reception centers are similar.
Turkey tore up the 2016 agreement to block migrants entering the EU.
Although Europe hopes to assist migrants and respects international law, it does not want overcrowding.
In 2015-16, a massive influx of refugees and migrants into the EU occurred – many of them fleeing the Syrian civil war – which had a huge impact on trust within the EU.
A massive influx of migrants eroded the government's confidence in the management of external borders and asylum within the EU, also highlighting the futility of cooperation with the migrants' countries of origin.
Therefore, migrants became a political football, a populist's plum.
Under the leadership of President von der Leyen, the new EU Commission must regain control over the migration issue while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this reason, the EU needs to redefine its policies on four fronts, mobilizing member states to act in the interest of Europe.
Firstly, the EU must ensure the immediate security of its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping its internal borders open.
Any people who can freely move within a country, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, will not outsource control of their external borders to a state or region.
Securing the EU's external borders is a collective task and a national responsibility.
The EU's border and coast guard agency Frontex must be further strengthened and should be deployed jointly with member states - including coastal lines and airports.
The EU must also relaunch Operation Sophia, to combat illegal migration in the Mediterranean.
The EU needs to address economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Separating them has helped to prevent the asylum system from collapsing; addressing them separately would help ensure that migrants who are concerned about their safety can voice their rights.
Solving the EU's true economic and social needs requires an effective blue card or green card policy for economic migrants, and implementing a comprehensive immigration strategy.
The EU cannot afford to wait for the next migration crisis before considering the introduction of these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break down taboos.
Firstly, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a common interest issue.
Secondly, policies must clearly identify which migrants are welcome.
Thirdly, member states must answer which EU assistance they need to achieve a smooth migration process.
Lastly, visas and work permits must be brought to the forefront to facilitate the return of undocumented migrants to their countries of origin.
In accordance with the EU treaty, each member state needs to manage migrants coming from outside the EU itself.
However, if governments reach an agreement on the EU's overall migration goals, that would be a major step forward.
Conversely, member states can specify the countries of origin they wish to have as economic migrants and their specific requirements, as well as the EU budget resources they need to accommodate them.
Thus, the right to accept migrants will become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has already established a proactive immigration policy, selecting migrants based on indicators such as countries of origin, skill levels, and age brackets.
Europe can do the same.
Thirdly, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
Firstly, the EU must abandon the rigid requirement for the compulsory distribution of asylum seekers among its member states.
This requirement may still be feasible if the border, asylum, and immigration systems are fully effective.
Furthermore, it cannot be expected that the EU's frontline member states alone will solve the problem of illegal migrants crossing the external borders.
Refugee camps are overcrowded, migrants are subjected to mistreatment by authorities or forced to head north.
The responsibility of the first member state that migrants arrive in must be supplemented by the EU's cohesion.
The EU must also provide expertise and funding to rationalize the behavior and management capacity of national asylum institutions.
Only national decisions can ensure the integrity of the Schengen area and gain respect for national decisions across the entire Schengen zone.
After rationalizing the behavior and management capacity of national asylum institutions, asylum application processing procedures can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should build a stronger win-win cooperation with countries of origin and transit countries.
To ensure the return of migrants who are lawfully prohibited from entering the EU to their countries of origin, these connections are crucial.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as plans in areas such as security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's migration goals, as well as skills cooperation to prepare for European work posts, can be offered to third countries eager for stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root cause of migration.
This includes the demographic explosion in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and a shortage of job opportunities.
The EU's assistance should focus on rebuilding stability and reducing risks through support for security, community resilience and good governance.
This success can make investments safer, unlock private and domestic finance, thereby achieving national economic growth, job creation, and providing alternatives to migration.
The new EU Commission has the opportunity to move the EU away from its instinctive reaction to the migration crisis and towards a more cohesive and sustained policy, whether internally or externally.
We must not let this opportunity slip away.
